The White House has released a proclamation by President Barack Obama declaring April 14, 2011, as Pan American Day and the week of April 10-16, 2011, as Pan American Week. The proclamation celebrates the close cooperation and partnership between countries in the Americas and highlights the shared values and interests that unite the region. It also recognizes the historical milestones, such as the formation of the Organization of American States and the commitment to democracy, as well as the designation of 2011 as the International Year for People of African Descent. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of democracy, economic development, and human rights in the Americas, and calls for continued collaboration to overcome challenges and build a safer and more prosperous future. The proclamation encourages governors and officials across the United States to participate in appropriate ceremonies and activities to commemorate Pan American Day and Week.